<h3>The Question</h3>
<p>
    Backlog <a href="/backlog/1505-calibrator-model-batch-context-cost-so-work-bound-stops-the-/">#1505</a>
    asks how the batch calibrator (<code>scripts/backlog.mjs calibrate</code>) should model session
    capacity so that <em>every</em> batch informs the next batch's points budget. Today it trains a
    single-ratio estimate &mdash; <code>implied_capacity = points / (context% / 100)</code> &mdash; and
    averages it (context-weighted) <strong>only over capacity-bound stops</strong>
    (<code>budget</code>/<code>context</code>), excluding <strong>work-bound stops</strong>
    (<code>empty-pool</code>/<code>fork</code>/<code>gate</code>/<code>manual</code>/<code>outgrew</code>).
    But work-bound is the <em>designed-for common case</em>: the budget is <code>capacity &times; 0.6</code>,
    so a batch almost always exhausts its pool or hits a seam before saturating the window. The estimator
    therefore trains on the rare case and starves.
</p>

<h3>Live evidence &mdash; the starvation is real</h3>
<p>
    <code>capacity.json</code> holds 12 samples; <strong>11 are work-bound (<code>excluded</code>) and
    exactly one (<code>stopReason: context</code>) trains.</strong> So <code>capacityPoints</code> (93)
    rests on a single sample &mdash; a literal "mean of 1." The 12 <code>(points, context%)</code>
    close-out tuples:
</p>
<pre>(13,37) (57,49) (67,67) (50,47) (37,41) (23,33) (18,23) (34,44) (52,55) (72,51) (55,59) (48,65)</pre>

<h3>Recommendation (to ratify in #1505)</h3>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Pooled affine fit &mdash; ratified invariant, every batch contributes.</strong> Replace
        the single ratio (a line <em>through the origin</em>, i.e. zero fixed overhead) with
        <code>context% = overhead + cost&middot;points</code>, fit over <em>all</em> batches with a
        <strong>single</strong> intercept and shared slope. The intercept is the <strong>universal fixed
        overhead</strong> (pack/plan/gate &mdash; real work in every batch), so it averages out and every
        batch contributes to both parameters. The origin model is broken on two counts: it misattributes
        the measured overhead, and its stop-reason on/off gate discards ~90% of the data.</li>
    <li><strong>No work-bound intercept dummy.</strong> The skeptic argued work-bound stops inflate the
        intercept with non-productive context and should carry a separate offset; the live residuals
        refute systematic inflation (Finding 2), and a dummy is unidentifiable with one capacity-bound
        sample. Stop-reason is dropped.</li>
    <li><strong>Fork 1 &mdash; keep a data-driven safety margin.</strong> Replace the arbitrary
        <code>&times;0.6</code> with a margin sized to fit uncertainty (a lower confidence bound on
        derived capacity, or shrinkage toward the empirical median) &mdash; not the bare point estimate
        <code>(ceiling &minus; overhead) / cost</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Fit errors-in-variables (Deming), not plain OLS</strong>, and check heteroskedasticity as
        the sample grows &mdash; both axes are noisy (points is a coarse aggregate; context% is a single
        human eyeball reading), so OLS attenuates the slope and inflates the intercept.</li>
    <li><strong>Per-turn context% (trajectory data) is deferred, not the structural fix.</strong> It
        would enable a <em>per-event</em> waste correction (fork/gate tails) but is not needed for "every
        batch contributes" (the pooled fit already delivers that) and the data shows no systematic waste
        to correct. File the enabler only if a real per-event confound is later observed; bridge with the
        one-sided ratchet interim build.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Finding 1 &mdash; the affine fit shows a real, significant fixed overhead</h3>
<p>
    A plain OLS fit of <code>context% = overhead + cost&middot;points</code> over all 12 tuples:
</p>
<table>
    <thead><tr><th>Quantity</th><th>Estimate</th><th>SE</th><th>t</th><th>Note</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr><td>overhead (intercept)</td><td><strong>23.5%</strong></td><td>6.2</td><td><strong>3.79</strong></td><td>F(drop intercept) = 14.4 &mdash; overhead is real, not zero</td></tr>
        <tr><td>cost (slope)</td><td><strong>0.549 %/pt</strong></td><td>0.131</td><td>4.2</td><td>24% relative SE</td></tr>
        <tr><td>R&sup2;</td><td>0.638</td><td></td><td></td><td>n = 12, 2 params</td></tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>
    The single-ratio-through-origin model is decisively wrong: a ~24% fixed overhead exists that the old
    model spread into <code>cost&middot;points</code>, systematically <em>under</em>-estimating implied
    capacity on small (work-bound) batches &mdash; precisely why excluding them looked necessary. The
    affine model measures the overhead explicitly, so the exclusion is no longer needed.
</p>

<h3>Finding 2 &mdash; the skeptic pass, and where it was itself refuted</h3>
<p>
    An adversarial skeptic pass raised four objections to the affine default. The first &mdash; that
    work-bound stops <em>inflate</em> the intercept and need a separate offset &mdash; was tested against
    the data and refuted; the rest stand:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>"Work-bound context inflates the intercept" &mdash; REFUTED by the residuals.</strong>
        The fixed overhead the skeptic names (pack/plan/gate) is <em>universal</em> &mdash; real work in
        every batch &mdash; not a work-bound-only waste; it is exactly the affine intercept and averages
        out across all batches. The live residuals show no systematic inflation: mean residual is
        <strong>&minus;0.5 for work-bound vs +5.3 for the single capacity-bound batch</strong> (the
        saturating batch sits <em>above</em> the work-bound cloud, not below), and the two <code>fork</code>
        batches split <strong>+6.4 / &minus;10.4</strong>. We also estimate from a work-bound-dominated
        population to predict a work-bound batch &mdash; like-for-like, no extrapolation bias. So the
        model collapses to a single pooled intercept and stop-reason is dropped. (The intercept is
        strongly significant &mdash; t = 3.79, F = 14.4 &mdash; confirming overhead is real, just not
        stop-specific.)</li>
    <li><strong>The fit is too thin to retire a margin &mdash; STANDS.</strong> Leave-one-out moves the
        slope across 0.46&ndash;0.67 and the derived budget@85% across 98&ndash;123 pts &mdash; a ~25%
        swing from a single dropped sample. A marginless budget removes the buffer that absorbs this and a
        regime change.</li>
    <li><strong>Errors-in-variables matters &mdash; STANDS.</strong> A Deming fit moves overhead
        23.5 &rarr; 20.0 and cost 0.549 &rarr; 0.629 (budget@85% 112 &rarr; 103) &mdash; a materially
        different model, confirming OLS attenuation. <code>corr(|resid|, points) = 0.20</code> hints at
        heteroskedasticity but is inconclusive at n = 12.</li>
    <li><strong>Trajectory data &mdash; deferred, not the structural fix.</strong> The within-batch
        trajectory could separate productive cost from the occasional fork/gate waste tail <em>inside</em>
        a batch &mdash; but with the inflation claim refuted, that is a <em>per-event</em> correction for
        a confound the data does not currently show, not the thing that makes "every batch contribute"
        (the pooled fit already does). Demoted from prerequisite to a contingency.</li>
</ul>
<p>Net: affine is right; the genuine surviving amendments are <strong>keep a data-driven margin</strong>
    and <strong>fit with EIV</strong> &mdash; the stop-reason carve-out the skeptic wanted is not needed,
    refuted by the residuals.</p>

<h3>Finding 3 &mdash; prior art: the methods are textbook</h3>
<table>
    <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Relevance</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td>Tobit / censored regression (Tobit 1958)</td>
            <td>OLS on a censored response is biased and inconsistent; Tobit recovers it via an ML
                likelihood (Olsen's 1978 <code>&delta; = &beta;/&sigma;</code>,
                <code>&gamma;&sup2; = &sigma;&#8315;&sup2;</code> reparameterization makes the
                log-likelihood concave). The item's original "Option 2" reached for Tobit because it
                modeled <em>latent capacity</em> directly (work-bound = right-censored on capacity). The
                affine reparameterization dissolves the censoring: a close-out tuple is an exact point on
                the cost curve regardless of <em>why</em> the batch stopped, and the fixed overhead is a
                single universal intercept &mdash; so no Tobit and no per-stop-reason offset are needed.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Recursive least squares with forgetting factor / sliding window (typical &lambda; &isin;
                [0.98, 0.995])</td>
            <td>The online form of the affine fit and the principled successor to the fixed 12-sample
                window: it discounts old regimes (e.g. a model change) continuously rather than by a hard
                cutoff &mdash; the natural home for the "adapt to a new model" requirement.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Deming / errors-in-variables regression</td>
            <td>The correct fit when both axes carry error, which they do here (coarse human context%
                reading; aggregated points). Plain OLS attenuates the slope.</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Classification</h3>
<p>
    This is <strong>internal batch tooling</strong>, not a shipped Web Everything standard &mdash; not a
    protocol, intent, block, or adapter, with no project-facing surface. It lives in the pure module
    <code>scripts/backlog/capacity.mjs</code> (consumed by <code>scripts/backlog.mjs calibrate</code>),
    so the standard classification questions resolve to N/A (dev-workflow tooling). The binding
    constraints are repo conventions: keep the estimator a pure, unit-testable module, and keep the
    human-supplied <code>--context-pct</code> contract until a harness enabler changes it.
</p>

